Titanic Project¶

Using Kaggle data about the unlucky passengers of RMS Titanic, we'll try to investigate what factors might be related to survival of some of the passengers. We'll first import necessary packages, read the data, and verify the data is read.

Question: Which factors, if any, made Titanic passengers more likely to survive?¶

We'll approach this question by treating Survived column as a dependent variable, and investigate variables Pclass, Sex, and Age variables to see if there are any correlations between them and Survived variable.

Data Wrangling¶

Let's first remove the columns we will not focus on, and check if there are any missing data points.

In [32]:
# using drop to remove columns
titanic = titanic_raw.drop(titanic_raw.columns[[0,3,6,7,8,9,10,11]], axis=1)
print "\nColumns (variables) we will focus:"
titanic.head()

# counting NaN values to see if there is any missing data

We have missing values in Age column. We can drop these values if this will not create a bias, but for example what if almost all the values dropped are of passengers with a specific characteristic that changed their survival rate? It would probably damage our model. So these are the questions to be answered:

  • Are the missing Age values meaningful in itself? (Only 12-18 age group are missing etc.)
  • Do the Pclass, Sex or Survived variables in rows that include missing Age values show a pattern different than general passenger data? (As in the above hypothetical scenario)

We first look at Age variable in itself.

In [5]:

We don't see any incredible nature in Age variable. One interesting thing is low ratio of children compared to the ratio in an arbitrary population. We can assume this might be attributed to the fact that a long voyage in a cruise is not feasible for children (they neither would get permission to go alone nor would raise enough money by themselves).

Let's look at the rows with missing Age data. For this purpose we will define a new data frame and remove the Age column as they will be NaN values. Then we will try to see if there is any pattern in Pclass, Sex or Survived paramaters that differs from main dataset.

In [14]:
# defining a new dataframe
titanic_nan = titanic[pd.isnull(titanic['Age'])]

# dropping Age column (all NaN)
titanic_nan = titanic_nan.drop(titanic_nan.columns[3], axis=1)

We see that for both males and females, survival rate is higher in passengers without an Age value.

Having analyzed the difference between the complete passenger data and data of passengers without an Age value, only significant difference is that passengers without an Age value have a higher survival rate, regardless of their Sex, but only in 1st and 2nd classes. Could it be due to relatively small sample size (30 in 1st class and 11 in 2nd class)? Or does it point at an information like "Passengers not having an ID had less chances for survival"? We don't know yet.

For our purposes, we will ignore the missing values in Age variable as we still have 714 data point when we include it in a particular analysis, and 891 when we don't. We will accept that missing Age values do not affect the relationship of Age, Pclass or Sex variable with the dependent variable Survived; with the disclaimer that the effect not having an Age does have on Survived variable must be analyzed further.

Also, we'll separate the Age variable to groups and create a variable called Age_Grouped as it will not be demonstrative to use Age as it is.

In [7]:
# creating age groups
age_groups = [0, 6, 12, 18, 65, 100]
age_group_names = ['0-6', '6-12', '12-18', '18-65', '65+']
titanic["Age_Grouped"] = pd.cut(titanic["Age"], age_groups, labels=age_group_names)

What are the initial thoughts here? Looking at Pclass variable, we see that 63% of 1st class passengers survived, while it is 47% in 2nd class. Finally in 3rd class we see that only 24% of passengers survived.

Looking at passengers' Sex, survival rate drops from 74% in women to 19% in men.

In Age_Grouped variable, we see that for most groups survival ratio is close. Only in age group 0-6 survival increases, and we note this down. While it also seems to drop in 65+ age group, it might be said 8 data points are too few to draw conclusions.

We'll now focus on Pclass and Sex variables with a two-way frequency table to see if we can draw further findings from survival ratio.

As we go from 1st class to 3rd class, we see that survival ratio falls from 97% to 50% in women and from 37% to 14% in men. Remembering that 0-6 aged children survived more, while it might be true that "Women and children first" mostly applied; socioeconomic status also was related to survival rate of passengers. Why is that? Why passengers from 3rd class had a lower survival rate? Is it because 1st and 2nd class consist more women and children than in 3rd class? Or the Class has an independent correlation with Survived?

In [49]:
pd.crosstab(titanic["Pclass"], titanic["Sex"], normalize = 'index')

We indeed see that ratio of women is higher in 1st and 2nd class than 3rd class. We also see ratio of women follows the opposite trend. This suggests that the independent paramaters that we presumed, namely Pclass and Sex, may actually be correlated - this might be a point to further investigate.

Lastly, even though it is out of our scope, we check the Cabin parameter to see if 3rd class passengers had an inherent disadvantage to reach the upmost deck where they could disembark.

In [54]:
# checking the distribution of passengers to cabins

titanic_cabin = titanic_raw.drop(titanic_raw.columns[[0,1,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,11]], axis=1)
titanic_cabin['Cabinned'] = titanic_cabin['Cabin'].str[:1]

Even though a great number of data points are missing, we see the general trend shows that going from A to G in Cabin means a higher Pclass value (lower socioeconomic status).

Now we check the layout of Titanic, and we see that going from A to G means that a passenger is located lower in Titanic, which probably decrease the chances of survival.

Conclusion¶

Our limited analysis shows that females survived in a higher ratio regarding Sex variable. Furthermore, we had already noted 0-6 aged children had a higher survival rate.

Higher percentage of women in 1st and 2nd class, and higher distance from 3rd class cabins to upper deck might have caused the lower survival rate of 3rd class passengers.

At this point, we must note that correlation does not imply causation. For instance, 0-6 age children might have a higher survival rate just because their mothers or nannies had a higher survival rate, which affected them too (For further analysis Parch variable might be investigated). This means Age might not have any statistically significant relation to Survived. If we want to create hypotheses to test, we might say that a passenger had a higher chance of survival if she is a female or that passenger is travelling 1st class. Our intuition also suggests these hypotheses would be correct, but we must rely on statistics and data analysis rather than intuition.
